ntegration testing with a real database instance verifies the threshold is actually passed to the database and applied correctly.","test_description":"Insert test documents into a real vector database, query with a search term that has no close semantic matches (e.g., 'flying cats' when database contains 'dog photos'), set a minimum relevance threshold (e.g., cosine similarity > 0.5), and verify the result set is empty. This requires a real database to ensure the threshold parameter is actually enforced by the database, not just by mock logic.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The end-to-end latency from receiving the query to returning re-ranked results stays below 2 seconds for the median case.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Unit or integration tests with mocked services would show instant responses and pass unconditionally, revealing nothing about real latency. Real bottlenecks come from embedding computation time, database latency, and LLM generation time. Only running end-to-end with real external services (embedding API, vector DB, LLM) captures actual performance characteristics and tail latency distribution.","test_description":"Run the API with 100+ realistic queries (varying in complexity and specificity), measure end-to-end latency from query input to re-ranked results output, and verify the median latency is below 2 seconds and p95 latency is within acceptable bounds. This requires real external services because mocked dependencies have zero latency, making the test meaningless. The LLM latency is often the dominant factor and is non-deterministic.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.6,"Agentic":0.3,"Workflow":0.05}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13914,"cache_read_input_tokens":0